bug.short_desc: Root handling in Inline Application and Dynamic resizing properties

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 772 Application to fix
Hi,
It seems that, in some cases, the properties that allows dynamic resizing of inline root elements don't work properly (see attachement for an example).
Best,
Benoît.
Alex, could you take a look whats wrong here and give the bug its importance?
This bug won't make it into the 1.3 release. Sorry for that.

Unfortunately it is not possible to fix this one. However, I found an easy workaround for this. The reason why the isle is not resizing automatically are the CSS rules for 'width' and 'height' of '100%'. --snip-- #isle { width: 100%; height: 100%; background-color: #F00 } --snip-- The browsers does apply those CSS rules setting the computed CSS values for 'width' and 'height' to absolute pixel values. The layout rendering process of qooxdoo does overwrite these values once the page is resized. This leaves the isle DOM node with absolute values for width and height and the isle isn't correctly resized anymore. A workaround would be to define the 'width' and 'height' CSS values inline. --snip--
--snip-- This way these values are over-ruling the ones which qooxdoo is calculating and everything is working correctly. The reason why we won't fix this issue is retrieving the values upon CSS rules is not trivial. qooxdoo does need to distinguish between absolute (computed) pixel values and absolute (computed) pixel values resulting of an applied CSS rule. This is not possible and therefore we can't find a working fix. I've update the documentation section mentioning that using CSS rules for styling 'width' and 'height' is not possible.

Hi Alex, Actually, it's this kind of workaround that I was using since the bug report. Except that I modified the inline style after the widget was rendered, I didn't know that inline styles wouldn't be overwritten by the widget style values. It's a pity that there's no real solution for this problem but I can accomodate myself with it... Best, Benoît. (In reply to comment #6) > Unfortunately it is not possible to fix this one.
